{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> κοιμ-ίζω</b>, <br /> post-[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], ={κοιμάω}, <b>put to sleep</b>, κ. ὄμμα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Rhesus” 826 (Lyric poetry); σὲ.. ἐκοίμισεν᾽ Αδρήστεια λείκνῳ ἐνὶ χρυσέῳ 3rd c.BC: Callimachus Epicus “Hymnus in Jovem” 47 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>harbour for the night</b>, οἶκος ἐν ᾧ τοὺς ξένους κοιμίζουσιν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Dosiadas Epigrammaticus cited in 2nd c.AD: Athenaeus Epigrammaticus 4.143c, cf. LXX.3Ki.3.20 \">LXX+3rd c.BC+</a>]; <b>still, calm</b>, ἄημα πνευμάτων ἐκοίμισε στένοντα πόντον, i.e. the winds <b>suffered</b> the sea <b>to rest</b>—by ceasing, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 674 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; θάλασσαν ἀγρίαν ἐκοίμισαν (i.e. οἱ δαίμονες) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"“Anthologia Graeca” 9.290 (1st c.AD: Philippus Epigrammaticus): _metaphorically_, κ. τὸν λύχνον\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>] <b>put it out</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Nicopho Comicus 7 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; μεγαλαγορίαν κ. <b>lay</b> pride <b>to sleep, quench, stifle</b> it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 184 (Lyric poetry); κ. θυμόν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 873a; τὰς λύπας 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Symposium” 2.24; πόθον “Anthologia Graeca” 12.19 * (1st c.BC: Meleager Epigrammaticus)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐλπίδας οὐ θάλαμος κοίμισεν, ἀλλὰ τάφος[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 7.183 (Parmenio Epigrammaticus)\">Refs</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, παῖς κοιμίζεται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 826; τὸ θηριῶδες κ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 591b. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> of the sleep of death, καλῶ δ᾽.. Ἑρμῆν χθόνιον εὖ με κοιμίσαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 832; Τιτάνων γενεὰν.. Ζεὺς κοιμίζει φλογμῷ 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 473 (Lyric poetry), compare “Hipp.” 1386 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>middle</i>, κοίμισαί μ᾽ ἐς Ἅιδου [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Tr.” 594 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> Grammars, <b>soften the accent</b> (from acute to grave), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Scholia 2nd c.BC: Dionysius Thrax Grammaticus p.23 H., Scholia 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.334; compare{κοίμισις} 11. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G8044","accentedUnicode":"κοιμίζω","shortDef":"to rest","mediumDef":"to rest","stepGloss":"to rest","stepTransliteration":"koimizō","count":0,"_step_Type":"verb"}]}